It is one of over 60 member species of the genus ''[[Rhipidura]]'', commonly known as the fantails. Within the genus it belongs to a group of five closely related species: ''R. rufidorsa'', ''R. brachyrhyncha'', ''R. dahli'', ''R. teysmanni'' and ''R. rufifrons''. A molecular phylogeny study showed the [[rufous fantail]] ''(Rhipidura rufifrons)'' to be its closest relative.<ref name="phylogeny">{{cite journal | last1=Nyári| first1=Árpád S| last2=Benz| first2=Brett W.| last3=Jønsson | first3= Knud A. | last4=Fjeldså |first4=Jon | last5=Moyle | first5=Robert G.| title=Phylogenetic relationships of fantails (Aves: Rhipiduridae)  | journal=[[Zoologica Scripta]] | volume=38| issue=6| year=2009| pages=553–561| doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2009.00397.x| s2cid=84865515}}</ref>

It forms a [[superspecies]] with ''R. rufifrons'' and ''R. semirubra'', and all three are often considered conspecific. All are part of a larger species group that also includes ''R. teysmanni'', ''R. superflua'', ''R. dedemi'', ''R. opistherythra'', ''R. lepida'', ''R. rufidorsa'', ''R. dahli'', ''R. matthiae'' and ''R. malaitae''.<ref name="Mayr">{{cite journal | last1=Mayr | first1=Erynst | last2=Moynihan | first2=Martin | title=Evolution in the ''Rhipidura ruffifrons'' group | journal=[[American Museum Novitates]] | issue=1321| year=1946| pages=1–21| hdl=2246/4445 }}</ref>

